How you end your myth-busting message depends on whether youâ€™re in the middle of unpacking multiple MYTHS, or transitioning into the next part of your message. 
If youâ€™re finishing your myth-busting and transitioning to the next part of your message (your Solution Pitch), ask a rhetorical question about what the real SOLUTION to the PROBLEM is. Hereâ€™s an example:
â€œSo, if finding good clients isnâ€™t just about knowing where to look, and if itâ€™s not about building a big Social Media following, and if itâ€™s not about writing a book, how do you find clients willing to pay 5x or 10x what theyâ€™re paying you now?â€
If youâ€™re finishing one MYTH and about to debunk the next, use one of these two approaches:  
1.	Ask whether they want to pay the price of the MYTH (or continue paying it), for example: â€œDo you really want to keep using shortcuts that make your sales slumps last longer than they should?â€
2.	Use a metaphor, anecdote, expert quote, or joke to reinforce how pointless, irrational or ridiculous the MYTH is. 
The example below shows you the third myth of a myth-busting message, and how weâ€™d transition to the next section. 
********************************EXAMPLE********************************
