Formula #3: The Bold Promise Opening
This is a super powerful way to open a sales letter, ad, email, or direct mailer. The formula is simple, you PROMISE an outcome by a specific DEADLINE, and assure them that it will happen without the EXTERNAL OBJECTION and despite the INTERNAL OBJECTION. You can also add some CONDITIONS to tell your prospect how easy, fast, powerful, etc (see my â€œSuper Sevenâ€ in Chapter XI) it will be for your prospect to experience the PROMISE. Finally, use your RISK REMOVAL offer to tell them what youâ€™re willing to do if they buy and use your product or service, and the PROMISE doesnâ€™t happen by the DEADLINE. 
1.	PROMISE: youâ€™ll lose 10% of your body fat.
2.	DEADLINE: in the next 90 days. 
3.	EXTERNAL OBJECTION: starving yourself, wrecking your metabolism, or lowering your energy level.
4.	INTERNAL OBJECTION: even if youâ€™ve been overweight for years and tried multiple diets with no results.
5.	CONDITIONS: follow a 30 minute daily workout, and a simple done-for-you nutrition plan. 
6.	RISK REMOVAL: refund your money and pay you $100. 
You can start this opening with a â€œDear [AUDIENCE]â€ statement, as in the example below. Next, use one of the following three frameworks to finish your opening: 
â—	Option #1: Question w/Contrast
Ask a series of questions that focus on their desire to experience the PROMISE by the DEADLINE, without the INTERNAL OBJECTION and despite the EXTERNAL OBJECTION. 
These questions can start with "Do you wantâ€¦" or â€œAre you readyâ€¦" or â€œWhat if you couldâ€¦â€ or â€œHow would you likeâ€¦â€ or â€œHow would your ___ change ifâ€¦â€ or â€œCan you imagineâ€¦â€ and include the first four variables covered above. 
â—	Option #2: Future Pacing
Use a â€œimagineâ€ or â€œpictureâ€ or â€œHow would yourâ€¦â€ or â€œHow would you feel ifâ€¦â€ or â€œWhat would yourâ€¦â€ or â€œWhat would you do/think ifâ€¦â€  statement to get your prospect to see themselves experiencing the PROMISE by the DEADLINE, without the INTERNAL OBJECTION and despite the EXTERNAL OBJECTION. This is called â€œfuture pacing,â€ a topic I cover in detail in my article below. 
www.sethczerepak.com/hypnotic-copywriting 
â—	Option #3: If ___, Then ___
Use a series of â€œIf___, then___â€ statements that affirm your prospectâ€™s desire to experience the PROMISE by the DEADLINE, without the INTERNAL OBJECTION and despite the EXTERNAL OBJECTION. 
These statements can start with "If you wantâ€¦" or â€œIf youâ€™re readyâ€¦" or â€œIf you couldâ€¦â€ or â€œIf I could show youâ€¦â€ and include the first four variables covered above, finishing with either a statement like one of these:
â—	â€œ...youâ€™re going to love this program.â€
â—	â€œ...this is the program youâ€™ve been searching for.â€
â—	â€œ...starting this program will be the best decision of your life.â€
â€¦or a question like one of these:
â—	â€œ...would you be interested?â€
â—	â€œ...what would your life look like?â€
â—	â€œ...how soon would you want to get started?â€
OPTIONAL: include a sentence summarizing the CONDITIONS for your prospect to experience the PROMISE summarized above.
Finish your Bold Promise Opening a â€œ(If ___), hereâ€™s whyâ€¦â€ followed by a summary of your RISK REMOVAL to transition to the next section of your sales letter. 
EXAMPLE #1: Question w/Contrast
********************************EXAMPLE********************************
What if you could lose 10% of your body fat in the next 90 days, without starving yourself, wrecking your metabolism, or lowering your energy level? 
