Element #4: Uniqueness
Uniqueness is how you show your prospect that they canâ€™t get the â€œsame thingâ€ from anyone else. This is the most important element of positioning. Itâ€™s also the most widely neglected and easily misunderstood. It starts with finding your Unique Selling Proposition (aka, â€œUSPâ€). Your USP is the one thing that makes your brand, product, or service uniquely superior to your competitor. The worst (and sadly the most common) attempts to define a USP sound like this:
â—	â€œWe stand by our product.â€
â—	â€œWe pride ourselves on quality and service.â€
â—	â€œWe guarantee your satisfaction.â€
â—	â€œWe really care about our customers.â€
These are a five star snoozefest, and not even close to being Unique Selling Propositions. Theyâ€™re vague cliches that circle directly back to the question theyâ€™re supposed to answer:
â€œCan I get the same thing somewhere else?â€
Youâ€™re convinced that your product or service really is better than competitors. Your existing customers probably are too. But your prospects havenâ€™t used your product or service yet. They have no first-hand experience as to whether youâ€™re telling the truth or what you even mean by vague statements about â€œquality,â€ â€œservice,â€ or how much you â€œreally careâ€ about your customers.
Your USP shouldnâ€™t require your prospect to know something that only you and your existing customers can know. It shouldnâ€™t even try to convince them that youâ€™re better. It should explain how youâ€™re different in a way that adds value for them. Here are three rules for defining your USP:
1.	Make it Specific: Donâ€™t use abstract words or phrases that require extra explanations or examples. This includes words like â€œquality,â€ â€œsatisfaction,â€ â€œexcellence,â€ and â€œservices.â€ Your competitor can easily say the same things. Use concrete words and statements to make claims that can be objectively verified by examples, customer reviews, or scientific data.
2.	Make it Beneficial: Promise a specific benefit to your prospect and tie it to the thing that makes your product or service unique. This promise should be concrete enough to paint a â€œbefore and afterâ€ picture in the mind of your prospect. If your prospect can see a â€œmind movieâ€ of themselves living out this promised benefit, youâ€™re on the right track.
3.	Make it Unique: Your USP should allow you to claim something that your competitors canâ€™t claim without legal consequences. Some examples include patented formulas or other legally protected features of your product or your service. This is where most companies fail to define a solid USP. They make claims about why theyâ€™re better, but not how theyâ€™re unique.
Start your USP Pitch with a subheader (or callout) that starts with â€œHereâ€™s Why No Other [SOLUTION]â€¦â€ or â€œHereâ€™s a Promise (Offer, Guarantee, Commitment, etc) No Other [SOLUTION]â€¦â€ followed by clear and bold definition of your â€œhill to die on.â€ 
Next, clearly and state the mechanism (i.e., framework, method, ingredient, process, etc) that makes your product or service truly unique. Remember that if your competitor can honestly claim the same thing without legal consequences, itâ€™s not a USP. For extra effect, include the time, money, energy, experimentation, and other resources that were invested into creating and perfecting your USP. 
Next, tie your unique mechanism to the PROMISE youâ€™ve made to your prospect. You can do this by saying â€œThis is why weâ€™re the only [SOLUTION] thatâ€¦â€ or â€œThis is why we can promiseâ€¦â€ or â€œThis is how weâ€¦â€ or â€œThis means you getâ€¦â€ followed by a summary of the PROMISE, the DEADLINE, and how it can happen for your prospect without the EXTERNAL OBJECTION and/or despite the INTERNAL OBJECTION. 
Finish with a bold claim that your product or service is the only SOLUTION that offers this USP, and how you protect competitors from using it. Tie this off with your GUARANTEE and RISK REMOVAL or by making an open challenge for your competitors to outdo or to match your PROMISE.  
This example picks up where the superiority example left off. 
