Element #4: Guarantee
There are few things marketers kick, scream, whine, stamp their feet, and cry about more than my advice to create a rock-solid Guarantee. The point of a Guarantee is to take the risk off your customerâ€™s shoulders and place it on yours. Offering money back doesnâ€™t cut it. Your prospect is also investing their time, energy, and hope into buying and using your product or service. This is why you need two types of Guarantees. The first to make up for the money theyâ€™ve spent on your OFFER, the second to make up for their time. Hereâ€™s the most common objection I hear to this advice:
â€œWe canâ€™t promise anything if they donâ€™t use it!â€
Of course you canâ€™t. Iâ€™d never advise you to give someone a refund just because they ask for one. In fact, I honestly believe that if someone doesnâ€™t use your product or service, they donâ€™t deserve to keep the money they spent on it. I consider it a non-redeemable tax on laziness, and that money is better off in the hands of someone who will use it responsibly. I could go on a Lord of the Rings length rant about all the reasons you shouldn't give refunds to anyone who asks for one. 
The one exception to this is if they use your product or service as directed, and donâ€™t get the result youâ€™ve promised. This is the ONLY time you should honor your Guarantee and Risk Removal offer. That said, I strongly suggest you backup your PROMISE with two RISK REMOVAL offers. The first to make up for their money spent, and the second to make up for their time. For example, I offer $500 to anyone who reads and uses this book and doesnâ€™t honestly feel that itâ€™s the most effective AI Funnel Copywriting theyâ€™ve ever read. This does NOT mean Iâ€™ll give $500 to anyone who emails me making such a claim. Iâ€™m going to ask them specific questions to see whether theyâ€™ve read and used what I advise in this book. Iâ€™m also going to ask them which book they found to be more effective, and proof of the results they got applying what they learned in that book. If they canâ€™t answer these questions and show evidence that my advice failed to deliver, I assume they either didnâ€™t read or didnâ€™t use the book and are just out to make a quick $500. 
Bottom line, bold Guarantees should always come with conditions for your prospect to use what theyâ€™ve bought. If they do, and they donâ€™t experience the result youâ€™ve promised, only then are you responsible for making it up to them. Otherwise, theyâ€™re responsible for their lack of results, and you have a right to keep their money. Iâ€™m sure this will offend some sensitive readers. But if you understand and apply this advice, your sheer volume of sales will more than make up for any RISK REMOVAL offers you have to honor. 
The Guarantee formula is simple. Just state your Guarantee, and tell that youâ€™re offering it for one of the following reasons:
1.	Youâ€™re confident that it will deliver on your PROMISE. 
2.	You want your prospect to be confident in their purchase. 
Finally, use an â€œIf ___, then___ â€œ statement to anchor the CONDITIONS of your Guarantee to your RISK REMOVAL offers, as Iâ€™ve done in both the examples below. 
