Formula #3: Commitment Objections
This objection is simple. Your prospect has questions or doubts about whether the time and/or action required to achieve the PROMISE is either:
1.	Too much to ask
2.	Too good to be true
Let me start by cautioning you about the â€œtoo much to askâ€ prospects. You might not want these prospects to buy from you at all. This is especially true if youâ€™re marketing a service that requires your clients cooperation to achieve the PROMISE. The desire for fast results is often a symptom of prioritizing ease and urgency over diligence and value. Customers who think like that donâ€™t need to be persuaded to think differently. They need a paradigm shift. Even trained counselors have a hard time pulling this off, and thatâ€™s assuming they have the clientâ€™s full cooperation. 
