Formula #4: Character Objections
This objection is when your prospect is skeptical of your motives as a marketer. Let me start by clarifying the difference between a skeptical prospect and a cynical prospect. Skeptical prospects are genuinely interested in your PROMISE and just have a few last minute questions. These prospects are worth persuading. Cynical prospects are not. I discovered this difference when I was building and managing high-ticket sales call centers. Skeptical prospects would ask questions, and if they were satisfied with the answers, theyâ€™d become clients, and good ones. 
Cynical prospects, however, arenâ€™t looking for answers. Theyâ€™re searching for reasons to say no. Theyâ€™ll hound you with questions until they find these reasons, and if they donâ€™t find them, theyâ€™ll make them up by twisting or distorting your answers. Many times, they wonâ€™t buy, and if they do, theyâ€™ll be the most likely to complain, to demand more than what theyâ€™ve paid for, or even demand a refund, only to trash your reputation on social media or a review site. 
Cynical people are determined to be happy and to validate their chronic unhappiness as the â€œrightâ€ view of the world. They spend their energy searching for ways to justify their unhappiness. If they donâ€™t find any, they invent reasons out of thin air and they turn people and businesses into targets in the process. In my opinion, no self-respecting sales person or marketer should waste their time trying to persuade a cynical prospect. As Jesus said, donâ€™t cast pearls before swine. 
I said all that to say this  formula isnâ€™t designed to persuade the cynical. Itâ€™s designed for skeptical prospects who just need a shift in focus. At this stage of your funnel, you should have already answered your prospectâ€™s Character objections. Now youâ€™ll simply address their last minute objections by turning their focus back on what your OFFER will do for them. This will make a reasonable prospect set their fear aside and make the decision that best serves their interests. If this doesnâ€™t work, you either didnâ€™t address this objection early enough in your funnel, or your prospect is cynical and not worth turning into a customer.  
BTW, before I show you this formula, letâ€™s clear up a gross misunderstanding about its origins. Itâ€™s not mine. Itâ€™s also not Russel Brunson's who, in my opinion, unethically claims credit for it. Dan S Kennedy is the earliest copywriter I saw sharing this formula, and even he admits that it might have come from an old school direct response ad, but that he canâ€™t quite remember. The important point is that itâ€™s damn effective. 
Start this message with a subheader that describes the objection your prospectâ€™s language, like this:
1.	â€œArenâ€™t You Just Trying to Make Money With This?â€
2.	â€œIf You Really Want to Help, Why Isnâ€™t This Free?â€
3.	â€œArenâ€™t You Just Saying All This to Make a Sale?â€
Next, use a â€œIf ___, then ___â€ to reaffirm their objection as the reason theyâ€™re still reading, listening, or watching instead of buying. The closer this objection matches their internal dialogue, the better. 
Next, bluntly tell them that it makes no difference to you whether they buy or not. Give them several â€œIt wonâ€™tâ€¦â€ or â€œI wonâ€™tâ€¦â€ statements that describe how your life will go on whether they buy or not. 
Next, flip the script by telling them that it will have a dramatic impact on their life, not only today, but long after today. Give them several â€œIt willâ€¦â€ statements that describe the physical, financial, social, and emotional impact your PROMISE will have on them.
These benefits should go beyond the scope of your product or service, to address larger changes in your prospectâ€™s lifestyle. The better you do at expanding the scope of these benefits, the more compelling this message will be. See my three copywriting articles below for details on this technique. 
